    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>U. S. Cir Court Clerk's Office</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St Paul</placeName>
                <date>Feby 12, 1863</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Your letter of <date>2d Feby.</date> With<lb/> rect. for School
                books and also the Book<lb/> came to hand; I have again to call<lb/> your attention
                to a little neglect on<lb/> your part, not so much on account of<lb/> the amount,
                but that matters may be<lb/> properly understood between us.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Soon after I forwarded to you, the<lb/> amount for school books. I
                also forwarded<lb/> $3. the amount of my subscription to<lb/> the “Occident” for one
                year and $1.50 for<lb/> 2 Copies of <persName>Dias'</persName> letters, sent to me
                leaving<lb/> the Bible only in my charge unpaid for</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>did not that letter come safe to hand.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am sorry to trouble you with this<lb/> small matter; but if I am
                to attend<lb/> to any business for you it is better that<lb/> we should have all
                items, properly ac-<lb/>counted for. I will communicate<lb/> with you hereafter in
                regard to send-<lb/>ing books here to be disposed of &amp;<lb/> in the meantime will
                do what I<lb/> can to procure subscribers for you, in<lb/> this section, my time is
                not so much<lb/> occupied but that I can attend<lb/> to any thing you may desire
                here!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The Occident to <persName>Mr Marcuson</persName> and<lb/> myself
                comes to hand! <persName>W. M.</persName> I trust<lb/> will content himself here
                tho' from<lb/> all I have seen of him his great<lb/> fault is being unsettled!
                    <sic>he</sic> is a<lb/> frequent visitor at my house and</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>both <persName>Rachel</persName> and myself desire a<lb/> great deal of information
                from in regard<lb/> to Religion in which we both take great<lb/> interest.
                    <sic>he</sic> is no doubt a very learned<lb/> man; and should be at the head of
                a<lb/> large congregation!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We all continue well and <persName>Nelle</persName> quite<lb/>
                <sic>dilighted</sic> that you should remember,<lb/> her. I have read the “Jews &amp;
                Inquisition<lb/> and with <persName>Mr Marcuson's</persName>
                    explanaturis<add>?</add>, I have<lb/> been delighted with it, and will
                cheerfully<lb/> remit the price of any similar work<lb/> you can forward to me.</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">Yours very Respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">J N Cardoza</persName>
            </p>
            <p><persName>Mr. Abm Elfelt</persName>, is well and sends respects &amp;c</p>
        </body>
